usefulness_explanation: It didn't explain a lot of terminology that was used immediately in the tutorial, like edges or directed edges.
learnability_explanation:
When you're teaching a new language, only present one way to do each action. Don't have both "connect x with y" and "x -> y" at the very beginning, that's just needlessly confusing.

Also the align keyword makes no sense, you should be able to select multiple nodes then put "align:vertical" as an attribute.

And the "step" keyword isn't intuitive by any means. Maybe change it to "frame" or "animate" or something.
readability_explanation: It's very convenient that you can define nodes on the fly, but I bet I could write some very very unreadable code with nodes defined in weird places, then have a lot of very confusing selectors set and unset styles. The examples given were clean, but I feel like it allows for some really unclean code to be written.
usability_explanation:
It was fine, I got through the basic tutorial just fine. But aligning things was hard, and I found it frustrating that I couldn't rotate it the way I want and say "n1 above n2" or something.

Also in more complex graphs with weird node names, it becomes very easy to accidentally create new nodes when you typo an existing node name.
